    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.36a.61"/>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <add><note type="authorial">Dept. of Modern Languages</note></add>
                        <lb/>
                    The Commonwealth of Massachusetts
                        <lb/>
                    Southeastern Massachusetts University
                        <lb/>
                    North Dartmouth, Massachusetts 02747
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>16 October 72</dateline>
                    
                    <salute>My dear Dr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I've just finished reading your latest <unclear>work</unclear> <hi rend="caps">ALL IS BUT A BEGINNING</hi> and can't <unclear/> this present, ubiquitous desire to request that you inscribe and date <unclear>this</unclear> superb tome for me. One Thing is <unclear>a</unclear>bsolutely certain, Dr. Neihardt, when Dick Cavett expresses, in his introductory <unclear>r</unclear>emarks, that one feels "an instant <unclear/>" with you, no matter what his <unclear>a</unclear>ge, race, religion or occupation may be. In complete candidness, the book is a sheer <hi rend="underline">tour de force</hi>, as are all your many, other volumes which I unequivocally treasure and esteem, more than I possibly or adequately can state. You write so clearly and so well. In today's day and age, it's a blessed joy that we have writers of your caliber and magnitude.</p>
                
                <p>To expedite the safe, albeit snail-like return of my precious copy, you'll find a stamped, self-addressed envelope. Thank you so very much, Dr. Neihardt.</p>
                
                <p>You made a 90-minute appearance on the Dick Cavett Show. I watched and watched for it, but for some reason or another, I missed it. Will there be a rerun of this show in the foreseeable future? Are you presumably in the stages of a second volume of your autobiography? If so, when will this volume be ready for perusal? My younger
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    The Commonwealth of Massachusetts
                        <lb/>
                    Southeastern Massachusetts University
                        <lb/>
                    North Dartmouth, Massachusetts 02747
                </fw>
                
                    brother &#8212; equally a longtime, enthusiastic reader of yours &#8212; wants to know if you have a favorite among your many books &#8212; or is there one which you consider your best? I do hope you won't mind responding to these queries, Dr. Neihardt.</p>
                    
                <p>I hope and pray that your health is good and that you continue to create for many, many years to come. Your volumes of fiction, poetry, philosophy and now your autobiography grace my library shelves and illuminate my very mind and spirit. Bless you, Sir.</p>
                
                <p>With kindest personal regards and renewed esteem for <hi rend="caps">ALL IS BUT A BETINNING,</hi> I am</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours respectfully,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Melvin B. Yoken</signed>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Dr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>5835 Vine Street</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Lincoln, Nebraska</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>68505</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </closer>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">61</fw>
                
            </div1>
